docs.abstract: The Trump era spurred them to collective action. But the work has just begun.
docs.snippet: The Trump era spurred them to collective action. But the work has just begun.
docs.lead_paragraph: This month, Big Tech pulled the plug on the loudest man on the internet. The decisions by Facebook and Twitter to remove Donald Trump coincided with a growing public concern about the power of tech platforms to invade privacy, monopolize markets and swing elections. Bipartisan political actions, including major antitrust suits, are also underway. But as tech executives prepare for these battles, they also face an adversary closer to home: the militant white-collar tech worker.

headline.main: Silicon Valley Workers Have Had Enough
headline.print_headline: Silicon Valley Workers Have Had Enough

byline.original: By Ben Tarnoff and Moira Weigel

docs.abstract: A Norwegian group filed a complaint with regulators, saying Amazon had deliberately made it difficult to end memberships to its Prime service. Groups in Europe and the U.S. back the effort.
docs.snippet: A Norwegian group filed a complaint with regulators, saying Amazon had deliberately made it difficult to end memberships to its Prime service. Groups in Europe and the U.S. back the effort.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Those who have tried ending a membership in Amazon Prime, the technology giant’s digital subscription service, may be familiar with the multi-click process: warnings that cancellation will mean losing “exclusive benefits,” and prompts to reverse course, or switch to an annual membership instead.

headline.main: Consumer Groups Target Amazon Prime’s Cancellation Process
headline.print_headline: Consumer Groups Fight Retention Tactics of Amazon Prime

docs.abstract: The app has renewed a debate about who holds power over online speech after the tech giants yanked their support for it and left it fighting for survival. Parler went dark early on Monday.
docs.snippet: The app has renewed a debate about who holds power over online speech after the tech giants yanked their support for it and left it fighting for survival. Parler went dark early on Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: From the start, John Matze had positioned Parler as a “free speech” social network where people could mostly say whatever they wanted. It was a bet that had recently paid off big as millions of President Trump’s supporters, fed up with what they deemed censorship on Facebook and Twitter, flocked to Parler instead.

headline.main: How Parler, a Chosen App of Trump Fans, Became a Test of Free Speech
headline.print_headline: A Web Haven  For Trump Fans Faces the Void

byline.original: By Jack Nicas and Davey Alba

docs.abstract: Connecticut’s top law enforcement official said on Wednesday that he was conducting an antitrust investigation into how Amazon runs its e-books business.
docs.lead_paragraph: Connecticut’s top law enforcement official said on Wednesday that he was conducting an antitrust investigation into how Amazon runs its e-books business.

headline.main: Connecticut is investigating Amazon’s practices in the e-books market.

docs.abstract: Microsoft, Starbucks and Amazon are among the companies offering the government assistance with logistics and operations.
docs.snippet: Microsoft, Starbucks and Amazon are among the companies offering the government assistance with logistics and operations.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon wrote to President Biden on Thursday offering to assist with communication and technology. Microsoft is opening up its largely empty office campus as a vaccination center as part of a broader partnership with the State of Washington. Starbucks is assigning workers from its operations and analytics departments to help design vaccination sites, donating the labor to the same state while continuing to pay employees.

headline.main: Help With Vaccination Push Comes From Unexpected Businesses
headline.print_headline: Unexpected Businesses Step Up to Lend Assets To Vaccination Rollout

byline.original: By Gillian Friedman and Lauren Hirsch

docs.abstract: Biden started off his presidency with a flurry of economy-focused executive orders. Netflix’s budget broke even — for the first time. And Parler won’t be back online anytime soon.
docs.snippet: Biden started off his presidency with a flurry of economy-focused executive orders. Netflix’s budget broke even — for the first time. And Parler won’t be back online anytime soon.
docs.lead_paragraph: All eyes are on President Biden right now. Here’s how his new policies will affect companies and households struggling to weather the pandemic economy — plus more of the week’s top business and tech news. Stay safe, everyone. — Charlotte Cowles

headline.main: The Week in Business: Biden Gets Down to Business
headline.print_headline: The Week in Business: Biden Gets Down to Business

docs.abstract: Faced with boycotts and criminal complaints, the director of “Tandav” made the edits this week. But that did not appear to satisfy some of the show’s critics, who called for him to be jailed.
docs.snippet: Faced with boycotts and criminal complaints, the director of “Tandav” made the edits this week. But that did not appear to satisfy some of the show’s critics, who called for him to be jailed.
docs.lead_paragraph: ARPORA, India — The director of a big-budget Amazon web series has bowed to pressure from Hindu nationalists and cut several scenes that they had deemed offensive, demonstrating the sway of a powerful political movement that strives to reshape Indian society.

headline.main: Director of Amazon India Drama Cuts Scenes Amid Outcry From Hindu Nationalists
headline.print_headline: Director of Amazon Drama Cuts Scenes After India Protests

byline.original: By Suhasini Raj and Jeffrey Gettleman

docs.abstract: The 1978 novel, which Amazon recently removed from its site, depicts a right-wing assault on the Capitol. Scholars say the parallels with last week’s insurrection are clear and chilling.
docs.snippet: The 1978 novel, which Amazon recently removed from its site, depicts a right-wing assault on the Capitol. Scholars say the parallels with last week’s insurrection are clear and chilling.
docs.lead_paragraph: In “The Turner Diaries,” a group of white supremacists attacks the Capitol in an effort to overthrow the U.S. government. Dozens are killed in the assault, including members of Congress and their staffers. But in the insurrectionists’ view, the greater victory is symbolic.

headline.main: How ‘The Turner Diaries’ Incites White Supremacists
headline.print_headline: A Novel That Guides White Supremacists

docs.abstract: Tech giants were right to ban the president. We still need to break them up.
docs.snippet: Tech giants were right to ban the president. We still need to break them up.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the days after Donald Trump whipped up a mob to overrun the Capitol in a desperate attempt to stop the certification of his defeat, many conservatives have voiced their outrage over the true victims of the failed putsch.

headline.main: The Scary Power of the Companies That Finally Shut Trump Up

docs.abstract: Airports across the United States are devoting more space to freight shipments as online shopping surges in the pandemic.
docs.snippet: Airports across the United States are devoting more space to freight shipments as online shopping surges in the pandemic.
docs.lead_paragraph: HEBRON, Ky. — Since the pandemic started nearly a year ago, 15,000 fewer people arrive and depart daily from the Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport, known as CVG. Yet the 60 percent drop in passenger traffic is not so apparent on the airport’s four runways, which are handling a record amount of air cargo — nearly 4,000 tons a day.

headline.main: Air Cargo Construction Is Booming, Thanks to Amazon
headline.print_headline: Amazon Fuels a Boom in Air Cargo Projects
